Food writer Jack Monroe told the Work and Pensions Committee that the home situation of poorer youngsters is "already untenable". She said: "The impact of rising prices on millions of children in poverty in Britain, is going to be, in some cases, fatal. And that's not a term I use lightly." Ms Monroe said costly food was pushing families into horrible choices. She added: "That's not people deciding not to go to the theatre or have bottles of champagne." "That's people deciding 'we won't eat on Tuesday' or 'we'll turn the heating off' or 'we'll skip meals'." And almost half (42 percent) of families with children expect to have to borrow money, said research by comparethemarket.com. A third have struggled to pay their energy costs, rent or mortgage, said the poll of 2,100 people